Paragraph: (1) The work of Regin's hands was a shield, a great shield of iron. (2) Hammered out on that shield and colored with red and brown colors was the image of a Dragon, a Dragon lengthening himself out of a cave. (3) Sigurd thought it was the image of the most hateful thing in the world, and the light of the smithy fire falling on it, and the smoke of the smithy fire rising round it, made it seem verily a Dragon living in his own element of fire and reek. (4) While he was still gazing on the loathly image, Regin, the cunning smith, came into the smithy. (5) He stood by the wall and he watched Sigurd. (6) His back was bent; his hair fell over his eyes that were all fiery, and he looked like a beast that runs behind the hedges. (7) "Aye, thou dost look on Fafnir the Dragon, son of the Volsungs," he said to Sigurd. (8) "Mayhap it is thou who wilt slay him.". (9) "I would not strive with such a beast. (10) He is all horrible to me," Sigurd said. (11) "With a good sword thou mightst slay him and win for thyself more renown than ever thy fathers had," Regin whispered. (12) "I shall win renown as my fathers won renown, in battle with men and in conquest of kingdoms," Sigurd said. (13) "Thou art not a true Volsung or thou wouldst gladly go where most danger and dread is," said Regin. (14) "Thou hast heard of Fafnir the Dragon, whose image I have wrought here. (15) If thou dost ride to the crest of the hills thou mayst look across to the desolate land where Fafnir has his haunt. (16) Know that once it was fair land where men had peace and prosperity, but Fafnir came and made his den in a cave near by, and his breathings as he went to and came from the River withered up the land and made it the barren waste that men called Gnita Heath. (17) Now, if thou art a true Volsung, thou wilt slay the Dragon, and let that land become fair again, and bring the people back to it and so add to King Alv's domain.". (18) "I have nought to do with the slaying of Dragons," Sigurd said. (19) "I have to make war on King Lygni, and avenge upon him the slaying of Sigmund, my father.". (20) "What is the slaying of Lygni and the conquest of his kingdom to the slaying of Fafnir the Dragon?". (21) Regin cried. (22) "I will tell thee what no one else knows of Fafnir the Dragon. (23) He guards a hoard of gold and jewels the like of which was never seen in the world. (24) All this hoard you can make yours by slaying him.". (25) "I do not covet riches," Sigurd said. (26) "No riches is like to the riches that Fafnir guards. (27) His hoard is the hoard that the Dwarf Andvari had from the world's early days. (28) Once the Gods themselves paid it overas a ransom. (29) And if thou wilt win this hoard thou wilt be as one of the Gods.". (30) "How dost thou know that of which thou speakst, Regin? (31) ".

