“Oh,” said Caleb, gently, with a slow swing of his head on one side, as he seated himself and laid his hat on the floor. (7) He looked at the ground, leaning forward and letting his long fingers droop between his legs, while each finger moved in succession, as if it were sharing some thought which filled his large quiet brow. (8) Mr. Bulstrode, like every one else who knew Caleb, was used to his slowness in beginning to speak on any topic which he felt to be important, and rather expected that he was about to recur to the buying of some houses in Blindman’s Court, for the sake of pulling them down, as a sacrifice of property which would be well repaid by the influx of air and light on that spot. (9) It was by propositions of this kind that Caleb was sometimes troublesome to his employers; but he had usually found Bulstrode ready to meet him in projects of improvement, and they had got on well together. (10) When he spoke again, however, it was to say, in rather a subdued voice—



“I have just come away from Stone Court, Mr. Bulstrode.”



“You found nothing wrong there, I hope,” said the banker; “I was there myself yesterday. (11) Abel has done well with the lambs this year.”

“Why, yes,” said Caleb, looking up gravely, “there is something wrong—a stranger, who is very ill, I think. (12) He wants a doctor, and I came to tell you of that. (13) His name is Raffles.”

He saw the shock of his words passing through Bulstrode’s frame. (14) On this subject the banker had thought that his fears were too constantly on the watch to be taken by surprise; but he had been mistaken. (15) “Poor wretch!” he said in a compassionate tone, though his lips trembled a little. (16) “Do you know how he came there?”

“I took him myself,” said Caleb, quietly—“took him up in my gig. (17) He had got down from the coach, and was walking a little beyond the turning from the toll-house, and I overtook him. (18) He remembered seeing me with you once before, at Stone Court, and he asked me to take him on. (19) I saw he was ill: it seemed to me the right thing to do, to carry him under shelter. (20) And now I think you should lose no time in getting advice for him.” Caleb took up his hat from the floor as he ended, and rose slowly from his seat. (21) “Certainly,” said Bulstrode, whose mind was very active at this moment. (22) “Perhaps you will yourself oblige me, Mr. Garth, by calling at Mr. Lydgate’s as you pass—or stay! (23) he may at this hour probably be at the Hospital. (24) I will first send my man on the horse there with a note this instant, and then I will myself ride to Stone Court.”



Bulstrode quickly wrote a note, and went out himself to give the commission to his man. (25) When he returned, Caleb was standing as before with one hand on the back of the chair, holding his hat with the other. (26) In Bulstrode’s mind the dominant thought was, “Perhaps Raffles only spoke to Garth of his illness. (27) Garth may wonder, as he must have done before, at this disreputable fellow’s claiming intimacy with me; but he will know nothing. (28) And he is friendly to me—I can be of use to him.”



He longed for some confirmation of this hopeful conjecture, but to have asked any question as to what Raffles had said or done would have been to betray fear.



