Paragraph: (1) As they pulled and tugged and flopped Raggedy Ann about, somehow she fell over the side of the bridge into the water. (2) The puppy dogs were surprised, and Fido was very sorry indeed, for he remembered how good Raggedy Ann had been to him and how she had rescued him from the dog-pound. (3) But the current carried Raggedy Ann right along and all Fido could do was to run along the bank and bark. (4) Now, you would have thought Raggedy Ann would sink, but no, she floated nicely, for she was stuffed with clean white cotton and the water didn't soak through very quickly. (5) After a while, the strange puppy and Fido grew tired of running along the bank and the strange puppy scampered home over the meadow, with his tail carried gaily over his back as if he had nothing to be ashamed of. (6) But Fido walked home very sorry indeed. (7) His little heart was broken to think that he had caused Raggedy Ann to be drowned. (8) But Raggedy Ann didn't drown—not a bit of it. (9) In fact, she even went to sleep on the brook, for the motion of the current was very soothing as it carried her along—just like being rocked by Marcella. (10) So, sleeping peacefully, Raggedy Ann drifted along with the current until she came to a pool where she lodged against a large stone. (11) Raggedy Ann tried to climb upon the stone, but by this time the water had thoroughly soaked through Raggedy Ann's nice, clean, white cotton stuffing and she was so heavy she could not climb. (12) So there she had to stay until Marcella and Daddy came along and found her. (13) You see, they had been looking for her. (14) They had found pieces of her apron all along the path and across the meadow where Fido and the strange puppy dog had shaken them from Raggedy Ann. (15) So they followed the brook until they found her. (16) When Daddy fished Raggedy Ann from the water, Marcella hugged her so tightly to her breast the water ran from Raggedy Ann and dripped all over Marcella's apron. (17) But Marcella was so glad to find Raggedy Ann again she didn't mind it a bit. (18) She just hurried home and took off all of Raggedy Ann's wet clothes and placed her on a little red chair in front of the oven door, and then brought all of the other dolls in and read a fairy tale to them while Raggedy Ann steamed and dried. (19) When Raggedy Ann was thoroughly dry, Mamma said she thought the cake must be finished and she took from the oven a lovely chocolate cake and gave Marcella a large piece to have another tea party with. (20) That night when all the house was asleep, Raggedy Ann raised up in bed and said to the dolls who were still awake, "I am so happy I do not feel a bit sleepy. (21) Do you know, I believe the water soaked me so thoroughly my candy heart must have melted and filled my whole body, and I do not feel the least bit angry with Fido for playing with me so roughly!". (22) So all the other dolls were happy, too, for happiness is very easy to catch when we love one another and are sweet all through.



